WordPress is a content management system that enables you to set up your own business website, blog, or e-commerce platform.

WordPress is open source which means it offers you the flexibility of building on your own server without totally depending on them. You can hire developers to modify features to your preference or do it yourself using ready-made plugins by the community.

WordPress which was first released in 2003 is now the most popular CMS and powers over 40% of all of the websites on the internet today. It is built using the PHP programming language and has been maintained to date.

The major advantage WordPress has over other CMS is that it is flexible and easy to use and It requires little to no coding experience to get started.

It has a simple yet intuitive interface that allows anyone with a basic understanding of how it works to create interesting websites even if you haven’t built a website before.

Due to its open-source nature, it has a wide range of themes and plugins that you can use to customize your website, improve its functionalities and features. More of these themes and plugins are constantly been created by developers in the WordPress community.

## The Relevance of WordPress

Irrespective of the size of your website, WordPress is highly scalable and can accommodate all types, from small personal blogs to large e-commerce stores and corporate websites.

It is fully featured and offers great SEO support with plugins that can help you further optimize your content ranking and improve your visibility in search results.

There is no doubt that WordPress is one of the most versatile and powerful CMS for individuals as well as businesses.

You can create a professional-looking and functional website that meets your needs with WordPress, whether you are a blogger, a business owner, or a web developer, as WordPress provides you with the tools and resources you need.

As a result of its popularity, it also makes it an attractive target for hackers and cybercriminals interested in exploiting security vulnerabilities in the system.

In order to maximize the security of your WordPress site, you should enable two-factor authentication (2FA), which adds an additional layer of security to the login process, and is one of the best ways to protect your site.

## What is Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)?

Two-factor authentication (2FA) is a security measure to provide your information with an extra layer of protection as opposed to relying on a password alone.

With 2FA, You are required to provide an additional means of identification to gain access to your account, making it difficult for hackers to access your data even if they manage to get your password.

A 2FA can be something like a code generated by an app on your phone, a hardware key, or a biometric factor such as a fingerprint or facial recognition, confirming your identity before granting you access.

With the increasing amount of platforms that we sign up on, It is difficult to create unique passwords for each and keep track of them, this means Passwords can be easily guessed, stolen, or cracked through brute-force attacks.

Although, with 2FA, Hackers are required to also be able to access the second authentication which is incredibly hard to obtain or guess.

Businesses and Individuals who are conscious about their security always opt for 2FA to keep their online accounts secured. Even organizations like Google and Twitter among others offer 2FA as an option for users. Internet security professionals also recommend it as a best practice for online security.

### There are different types of two-factor authentication:

**SMS-based 2FA**: This type requires that your mobile number is connected and a code is sent via SMS and you access your account using the code.

Although this isn’t an entirely safe method as SMS messages can be intercepted or delayed.

**App-based 2FA**: This type requires an app like Google Authenticator or Authy and it generates a unique code that you must enter to access your account.

Since these codes are time-sensitive and change within brief seconds, it is more secure and recommended.

**Hardware-based 2FA**: This type of authentication requires a physical key such as a Yubikey or Titan Security Key to access your account.

This is considered the most secure form of 2FA, as the key must be physically present to access your account.

**Overall**, 2FA is an essential security measure for anyone who wants to keep their online accounts safe from cybercriminals.

By adding an extra layer of protection to your accounts, you can greatly reduce the risk of unauthorized access and protect your valuable data.

## Why is Two-Factor Authentication Important for WordPress?

With WordPress powering over 40% of the websites on the internet and due to the fact that a good amount of website owners are not technically inclined, WordPress has been a frequent target for cybercriminals.

These criminals are always on the lookout for websites with weak passwords and once they are able to gain access to your website, They carry out all sorts of attacks like stealing users' personal information including credit card details, or wreaking havoc on your website as a whole.

The cyber threats and attacks are sophisticated and it has become more critical than ever to ensure that your website is properly protected against unauthorized access.

Enabling 2FA on your WordPress reduces the chances of unauthorized access and keeps your data safe. It is mandatory particularly when you manage sensitive information like Customer data, financial information, or intellectual property of any form.

Fortunately, there are several outstanding 2FA plugins available for WordPress. Some of the most popular options include WP two-factor authentication, Two-Factor, and WordPress two-factor authentication plugin.

These plugins make it easy to set up and manage 2FA on your WordPress site, regardless of your technical expertise.

If you are serious about protecting your WordPress site, want to reduce the risk of unauthorized access, and protect your valuable data. Follow these steps to get started!

## How to Enable Two-Factor Authentication in WordPress

With the different plugins available in the WordPress marketplace, It is effortless to enable 2FAs and for this article, I will be working with Google Authenticator and Two-Factor.

If you do not have your WordPress Website set up already, You can set up one within minutes using [https://instawp.com](https://instawp.com).

### Enabling Two-Factor Authentication Using Google Authenticator Plugin

Step 1: Click on Plugins on the sidebar of your WordPress Dashboard.

![](data:image/png;base64, align="left")

Step 2: Install and Activate the Google Authenticator Plugin

Click on Add New, and search for Google Authenticator. Install and activate the plugin.

![](data:image/png;base64, align="left")

Step 2: Configure the Google Authenticator Plugin

Once you have installed and activated the plugin, you need to configure it. Go to the Google Authenticator settings page by clicking on Settings &gt; Google Authenticator in your WordPress dashboard.

On the settings page, you can configure various options, such as:

Enabling 2FA for all users or just specific users

Setting the label that will appear in the Google Authenticator app

Enabling backup codes for users in case they lose access to their phone

Once you have configured the plugin, click on Save Changes to save your settings.

Step 3: Set up Google Authenticator on Your Phone

To use 2FA with the Google Authenticator plugin, you need to install the Google Authenticator app on your phone. Once you have installed the app, open it and follow the instructions to set it up. You will need to scan the QR code that appears on the Google Authenticator settings page in your WordPress dashboard.

Step 4: Test Your 2FA Setup

To test your 2FA setup, log out of your WordPress site and log back in. You should now be prompted to enter a code from your Google Authenticator app in addition to your password.

Conclusion

Enabling two-factor authentication is an essential step in securing your WordPress site.
